# Java Testing Rules

## Mandatory Framework

- `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` — the ONLY class-level annotation needed.
- **Never** use `@QuarkusTest`, `@QuarkusIntegrationTest`, Testcontainers, or RestAssured.
- AssertJ for all assertions: `assertThat(actual).isEqualTo(expected)`.

## Test Method Pattern

```java
@Test
void should_<expectedOutcome>_when_<condition>() {
    // Arrange — stub only what this test needs
    when(dependency.method(arg)).thenReturn(result);

    // Act
    var actual = sut.methodUnderTest(input);

    // Assert — specific values, never just assertNotNull
    assertThat(actual.field()).isEqualTo(expectedValue);

    // Verify side effects if they ARE the observable outcome
    verify(dependency).method(expectedArg);
}
```

## ArgumentCaptor

```java
// ALWAYS verify() BEFORE getValue()
verify(repo).save(captor.capture());    // capture
assertThat(captor.getValue()).isEqualTo(expected);  // then getValue()
```

## Strict Stubs

MockitoExtension enforces strict stubs. Remove any `when()` stub that is not called by the test method — it will throw `UnnecessaryStubbingException`.

## Coverage Goal

100% branch coverage. One `@Test` per branch. Never combine two branches in one test method.

## Branch Enumeration Checklist

Before writing tests, enumerate every branch in the target class:
- [ ] `if/else` — both conditions
- [ ] `switch` — each case
- [ ] `Optional.orElseThrow` — present and empty
- [ ] `try/catch` — happy path and exception path
- [ ] Loop — empty collection, single element, multi-element
- [ ] Ternary — true and false branches
